Bring a large #pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @button mushrooms{8%ounce} (skip if your mushrooms are pre-sliced!). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens.

Once water is boiling, add @tortelloni{18%ounce} to #pot{}. Reduce to a low simmer and cook until tender and floating to the top, ~{3-4%minutes}. Reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water (1 cup for 8 servings), then drain. Wash and dry pot.

While tortelloni cooks, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add mushrooms and scallion whites; cook, stirring occasionally, until mushrooms are browned and slightly crispy, ~{5-7%minutes}. Season with @pepper{}.

While mushrooms cook, in a #small bowl{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, scallion greens, @Parmesan cheese{3%tbsp}, half the @truffle zest{2%g} (you'll use the rest in next step), @olive oil{2%tbsp}, and @salt{1/2%tsp} (4 TBSP olive oil and 1 tsp salt for 8 servings).

In empty pot used for tortelloni, heat @cream sauce base{4%ounce} over medium heat until steaming and slightly bubbling, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Whisk in @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup} and @Italian cheese blend{1/2%cup} a handful at a time, alternating cheeses and whisking constantly between additions, until melted.

Remove from heat and stir in remaining truffle zest. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

> Stir in splashes of reserved pasta cooking water if sauce is too thick.

Add drained tortelloni and mushrooms to pot with sauce and stir to thoroughly combine. Transfer everything to an #8-by-8-inch baking dish{} (9-by-13-inch baking dish for 8 servings).

Top evenly with panko mixture and bake on top rack until topping is golden brown and sauce is bubbling, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Divide tortelloni bake between plates or serve family style directly from baking dish.

> Add some chili flakes from your pantry for a spicy kick!